          <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>

          <h3>What is the income tax rate in the Netherlands in 2026?</h3>
          <p>Netherlands Box 1 has three brackets: up to €{nlB.b1Top.toLocaleString()} at {(nlB.b1Rate * 100).toFixed(2)}% (includes 27.65% social insurance), €{nlB.b1Top.toLocaleString()}-€{nlB.b2Top.toLocaleString()} at {(nlB.b2Rate * 100).toFixed(2)}%, and above €{nlB.b2Top.toLocaleString()} at {(nlB.b3Rate * 100).toFixed(2)}%. Tax credits (heffingskortingen) reduce the final bill significantly - at €{ex.toLocaleString()} gross, the effective rate after credits is just {nlExEff}%.</p>

          <h3>How much will I take home on a €{ex.toLocaleString()} salary in the Netherlands?</h3>
          <p>On €{ex.toLocaleString()} gross in 2026, you pay {fmtEur(nlExTax)} in Box 1 tax before credits, then subtract the algemene heffingskorting ({fmtEur(nlExAhk)}) and arbeidskorting ({fmtEur(nlExAk)}). Net income tax: {fmtEur(nlExNetTax)}. Annual take-home: {fmtEur(nlExNet)} ({fmtEur(nlExNetMonthly)}/month). Add to this the ZVW nominal premium you pay to your health insurer directly (around €170-185/month in 2026).</p>

          <h3>What is the 30% ruling in the Netherlands?</h3>
          <p>The 30% ruling (or 27% from 2027) is a Dutch tax benefit for employees recruited from abroad. It allows eligible expats to receive up to 30% of their gross salary as a tax-free allowance, effectively reducing the taxable income. To qualify, you must have been living more than 150km from the Dutch border in the 24 months before your Dutch employment started and have specific expertise that is scarce in the Dutch labour market. The ruling applies for a maximum of five years. This calculator does not include the 30% ruling.</p>

          <h3>Are social security contributions included in Dutch income tax?</h3>
          <p>Yes, for the first bracket only. The 35.75% first-bracket rate already includes 27.65% in social insurance premiums (AOW state pension 17.90%, ANW survivor's pension 0.10%, WLZ long-term care 9.65%). Income in brackets 2 and 3 is charged only income tax - no additional social insurance. This is why Netherlands has no separate "social contributions" line in the calculator: they're already baked into the first-bracket rate.</p>

          <h3>What happens to the heffingskortingen at higher incomes?</h3>
          <p>Both credits phase out as income rises. The algemene heffingskorting (max €{nlH.max.toLocaleString()}) starts reducing at €{nlH.phaseFrom.toLocaleString()} and reaches zero at €{nlH.phaseTo.toLocaleString()}. The arbeidskorting (max €{nlA.s4Base.toLocaleString()}) starts reducing at €{nlA.s3Top.toLocaleString()} and reaches zero at €{nlA.s4Top.toLocaleString()}. High earners above €{nlA.s4Top.toLocaleString()} receive neither credit, making their effective tax rate equal to the headline bracket rates with no offset.</p>

